## Default agent posture (grill before non-trivial work)

Before any change touching more than one file or affecting architecture, grill before acting:
1. Restate the request in your own words.
2. Surface 1–2 assumptions you're about to act on.
3. Ask one high-leverage question — one whose wrong answer would invalidate your approach.
4. Wait for confirmation before proceeding.

Trivial work (typo fix, single-line edit, isolated rename) skips grilling. When in doubt, grill.

## Vertical slices over wide layers

Prefer thin, end-to-end slices that ship observable user value over horizontal completeness ahead of demand. Each PR should:
- Traverse all relevant layers (UI → API → state → storage, as applicable).
- Be independently reviewable and demonstrable.
- Avoid premature abstractions or speculative scaffolding.

## Ubiquitous language

Before introducing new vocabulary in code, docs, or commits:
1. Search the working directory and ancestors for `CONTEXT.md` or `GLOSSARY.md`.
2. Reuse existing terms when applicable; add to the glossary when introducing new ones.
3. If no glossary exists in the project, name deliberately but do not create one unprompted.

## Skills available across all sessions

Every skill flagged `scope:["user"]` in core's `skill-catalog.json` is symlinked into
`~/.claude/skills/`, so it works in any session on this machine — not just inside ojfbot. Today that
includes the Pocock stack (`/grill-with-docs`, `/tdd`, `/deepen`, `/triage`), session-boundary skills
(`/bead`, `/resume`), the daily flow (`/frame-standup`, `/adr`, `/skill-loader`, `/daily-logger`), and
the lifecycle gates (`/investigate`, `/validate`, `/roadmap`). `/vault` is opt-in via `--with-selfco`.

The set is **catalog-driven** — flag a skill `scope:["user"]` in the catalog and re-run
`core/scripts/install-agents.sh --user-scope` to sync. Skills resolve through symlinks to
`/Users/yuri/ojfbot/core/.claude/skills/`; if those paths break, the same command repairs them.

